  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,A)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X_\bullet ,A).       \tag{5.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2308</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.2.1</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>To each simplicial topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is associated a usual topological space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|X_\bullet |]]></fr:tex>, called its geometric realisation (see below).
    In the particular case where the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex> are discrete, we recover the usual notion of geometric realisation of a simplicial set.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>In [<fr:link type="local" href="S1968.xml" addr="S1968" title="Classifying spaces and spectral sequences">S1968</fr:link>], G. Segal defined the cohomology of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> with values in an abelian group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (|X_\bullet |,A)]]></fr:tex>.
    Under suitable hypotheses, the filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|X_\bullet |]]></fr:tex> by successive skeletons gives a spectral sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>460</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.1.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,A)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X_\bullet ,A).       \tag{5.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
            <fr:p>One of the interests in using this definition is that it also applies, for example, to the definition of the groups <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex>.
    We will adopt another definition, which is better adapted to sheaf-theoretic techniques.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>461</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="machine">#265</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>unstable-265.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Geometric realisation">Geometric realisation</fr:title>
                <fr:authors />
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>For an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex>, we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Delta _n|]]></fr:tex> the simple in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^{\Delta _n}]]></fr:tex> whose vertices are the set of basis vectors.
      We identify <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta _n]]></fr:tex> with the set of vertices of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|\Delta _n|]]></fr:tex>.
      Every function <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \Delta _n\to \Delta _m]]></fr:tex> extends by linearity to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|f|\colon |\Delta _n|\to |\Delta _m|]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be a simplicial topological space.
      Let
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         Y=\coprod _{n\geqslant 0}(X_n\times |\Delta _n|).       ]]></fr:tex>
      Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be the finest equivalence relation on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> for which, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon \Delta _n\to \Delta _m]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Delta )]]></fr:tex>, any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_m\in  X_m]]></fr:tex>, and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in |\Delta _n|]]></fr:tex>, we have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         (x_m,|f|(a))         \equiv  (f(x_m),a)         \operatorname {mod} R.       ]]></fr:tex>
      The <fr:em>geometric realisation</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is by definition
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         |X_\bullet |         = Y/R.       ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Backlinks">Backlinks</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2309</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.2.3</fr:number>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be an abelian sheaf on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    We can show (by example, using (III) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.xml" taxon="Examples" number="5.1.9" />) that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^\bullet ]]></fr:tex> always admits resolutions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> on the right such that
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^r(X_q,K^{p,q})       =0       \quad \text {for } p,q\geqslant 0 \text { and } r>0.     ]]></fr:tex>
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is such a resolution, then we canonically have that

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2248</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.3.1</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^n(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )         \simeq  \operatorname {H}^n(\mathrm {s}\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)).       \tag{5.2.3.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    It is easy to show directly that the right-hand side is independent (up to unique isomorphism) of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>;
    for what follows, we are free to <fr:em>define</fr:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )]]></fr:tex> by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.3.1" />.
    We can further show that the spectral sequence of the complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {s}\Gamma ^\bullet (X_\bullet ,K)]]></fr:tex>, filtered by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.9.3.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.9.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.1.12.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.1.12.2" /> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S=P^t]]></fr:tex>)

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2249</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.2.3.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.2.3.2</fr:number></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         E_1^{pq}         = \operatorname {H}^q(X_p,F^p)         \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{p+q}(X_\bullet ,F^\bullet )       \tag{5.2.3.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is independent (up to unique isomorphism) of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> (cf. <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="5.2.1.1" />).</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
